/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/board-review-data/scan-bundles/browser_terminal-9a77c4a.json:1335:        "summary": "One scorecard override on Q4: Phase 3 advisory computed amber via the standard rubric (q4_has_critical_on_default_path=False, since the dangerous-primitives regex doesn't read README or install-doc text). Phase 4 reads installation.md directly and finds the F0 typosquat URL on the Chrome install path. override_reason = harness_coverage_gap (second scan in the catalog to use this label, after Kronos Q4). Fix surface is phase_1_harness.py: add install-doc URL parsing with TLD-deviation detection; when that lands, the signal would fire without needing Phase 4 override."
/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/board-review-data/scan-bundles/browser_terminal-9a77c4a.json:1910:        "rationale": "The Phase 3 advisory computed amber via compute.py's Q4 rubric (q4_all_channels_pinned=False, q4_artifact_verified=False, q4_has_critical_on_default_path=False \u2014 compute cannot see the README text where the critical actually lives). Phase 4 reads installation.md directly (E1) and finds `chrome.google.cm/webstore/detail/browser-terminal/nbnfihffeffdhcbblmekelobgmdccfnl` \u2014 a Cameroon-TLD typosquat in the Chrome install path. Cross-referenced against `chrome.google.com`, this is not a different domain under Google's control; it is a `.cm` lookalike that would silently serve whatever page its owner configures. Separately, the Go native-binary install step is `sudo mv ~/Downloads/browser_terminal_linux /usr/local/bin/browser_terminal` with no integrity verification (E3, E4) \u2014 no checksum file in the release, no sha256 step in the README. For a tool whose installed form is a native-messaging shell bridge, this combination is not amber-level; it's red. Firefox users following the (correct) addons.mozilla.org URL do not hit the typosquat, but they do still hit the unsigned-binary step \u2014 so the red call applies on the Chrome install path and amber on the Firefox-only path.",
/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/board-review-data/scan-bundles/browser_terminal-9a77c4a.json:1911:        "edge_case": "The Q4 advisory signal `q4_has_critical_on_default_path` is derived from dangerous_primitives regex hits; it has no visibility into README / installation-doc text. Typosquat URL detection in install docs is specifically a harness-coverage gap, not a compute-signal calibration issue.",
/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/board-review-data/scan-bundles/browser_terminal-9a77c4a.json:1912:        "suggested_threshold_adjustment": "Add a harness step that fetches install-doc URLs (README hyperlinks matching /install/ or /web.?store/ or /addons/) and checks TLD against a reference list. Any Chrome install URL whose host is not `chrome.google.com` (or a redirect to it) should flag `q4_has_critical_on_default_path=true`. That single check would have fired on this repo without requiring Phase 4 override.",
/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/board-review-data/scan-bundles/browser_terminal-9a77c4a.json:1916:          "q4_has_critical_on_default_path",
/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/External-Board-Reviews/042026-schema-v12/deepseek-r3-raw.log:8:4. **Item D**: Chose nested partials to preserve per-family dangerous_primitives structure
/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/External-Board-Reviews/042026-schema-v12/pragmatist-r1.md:19:**On Q3 (D8-B2 scoped vs pure):** Pure D8-B2 (harness absorbs all transformer logic) would balloon the harness. The right split: field-name renames (`archived` → `is_archived`, `fork` → `is_fork`, `default_branch` → `default_branch_ref`, `reset` → epoch-to-ISO conversion, `dependabot_alerts` → `dependabot`, `osv_lookups` → `osv_dev`) are cheap harness changes — the harness just emits the schema-native names from the start. The shape deltas are different: the per-family `dangerous_primitives` structure (15 families × files[]) is harness-semantically correct — it's a natural representation of grep-per-pattern results. V1.2 schema should accept the nested per-family shape natively rather than forcing a flatten into a `hits[]` array at the harness level. The flatten loses the per-family aggregation context that the LLM would want for Phase 4 inference. Similarly, `manifest_files: [{path, format}]` — the harness emits the format field because it knows it; dropping it at transform time is a pure loss. V1.2 should accept it.
/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/External-Board-Reviews/042026-schema-v12/pragmatist-r1.md:43:- **D-RENDERER:** All renderer partial changes (surfacing `first_match.snippet`, per-family dangerous_primitives display) → V1.3 cycle. Not blocking V1.2 correctness.
/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/External-Board-Reviews/042026-schema-v12/pragmatist-r1.md:69:My weakest area here is the renderer surface (Q6) — I'm deferring it partly because I haven't read `render-md.py` and `render-html.py` deeply enough to know whether the D8-B2 shape changes (accepting nested per-family `dangerous_primitives` in V1.2) require partial rewrites before the renderer can process V1.2 forms at all. If the renderer directly consumes `code_patterns.dangerous_primitives.hits[]` today, and V1.2 changes that to a nested structure, then "defer renderer to V1.3" becomes inconsistent — you can't ship V1.2 forms that the V1.2 renderer can't render. The Systems Thinker should probe this coupling explicitly.
/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/External-Board-Reviews/042026-schema-v12/deepseek-r2-raw.log:7:3. **I identified a new disagreement**: The renderer's coupling to `dangerous_primitives.hits[]` structure means that adopting per-family nesting requires mandatory renderer changes, contradicting "Q6: no renderer changes."
