/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/board-review-data/scan-bundles/Baileys-8e5093c.json:3118:        "summary": "One scorecard override on Q4: Phase 3 advisory computed amber via the standard Q4 rubric (q4_has_critical_on_default_path=False by driver convention). Phase 4 authored F0 Critical \u2014 the reverse-engineered-API-library shape produces a default-path critical that isn't surfaced by any harness-derived signal. override_reason = signal_vocabulary_gap (5th Q4 use of this label in V1.2 catalog, 6th overall). Q1 red genuine (0 governance + 89.5% top-2 concentration), Q2 red genuine (PR #1996 stale-out + 14 runtime CVEs + 150-day stall), Q3 red genuine (no SECURITY.md + 0 advisories + documented disclosure-handling failure). This is the first V1.2 wild scan with all 4 cells RED \u2014 prior high-severity scans had at least one amber (typically Q3) softening the pattern."
/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/board-review-data/scan-bundles/Baileys-8e5093c.json:3726:        "Q4 signal `q4_has_critical_on_default_path` doesn't auto-fire from reverse-engineered-API-library category signals \u2014 Phase 4 authored the override (signal_vocabulary_gap). A compute derivation watching for README disclaimers + platform-operator-API install paths would close this signal class."
/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/board-review-data/scan-bundles/Baileys-8e5093c.json:3760:        "rationale": "Phase 3 advisory computed amber via the standard Q4 rubric (q4_has_critical_on_default_path=False by driver convention). Phase 4 has authored F0 Critical documenting the reverse-engineered-API-library shape: the library's ONLY function is to attach to WhatsApp Web servers using the consumer's account credentials, which is explicitly prohibited by WhatsApp's Terms of Service and carries documented account-ban risk. The README's own CAUTION-flagged disclaimer names this exposure. The `q4_has_critical_on_default_path` signal is a Phase-4-authored bool \u2014 compute has no harness-derivable signal for 'library category = ToS-violating third-party client' because the shape is a legal/operational-risk posture, not a grep-able primitive. This is a signal-vocabulary gap: Q4 asks about default-path safety, but the signal vocabulary doesn't capture 'using this library at all is a default-path risk' for reverse-engineered-platform-API libraries (Baileys, whatsmeow, anistr, discord.py-self, etc.).",
/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/board-review-data/scan-bundles/Baileys-8e5093c.json:3762:        "suggested_threshold_adjustment": "Add a compute-side derivation: if README contains explicit disclaimers about third-party-client status (phrases: 'not affiliated with', 'not endorsed by', 'unauthorized', 'reverse-engineered') AND install path connects to a named platform-operator API (WhatsApp, Discord, Instagram, etc.), auto-set q4_has_critical_on_default_path=True. The reverse-engineered-API-library category is distinctive enough to warrant its own compute-signal path.",
