/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/board-review-data/scan-bundles/WLED-01328a6.json:5461:        "rationale": "Phase 3 advisory computed amber via standard Q4 rubric (q4_has_critical_on_default_path=False by driver convention pending Phase 4 authoring). Phase 4 has authored F1 Warning describing default-no-auth webserver + CORS wildcard + unauthenticated `/reset` on user's firmware-controlling device. Combined with F0 (unresolved GHSA-2xwq-cxqw-wfv8 whose backport status is unknown), the default-path critical condition is true in judgment: a factory-default WLED on a LAN is controllable by any same-network webpage, and the undisclosed GHSA may contain a further vulnerability in that default path. The `q4_has_critical_on_default_path` signal is a Phase-4-authored bool, not a harness-derived signal \u2014 compute has no way to assess 'default install has no authentication + CORS wildcard' from grep-family primitives alone. This is a signal-vocabulary gap: the concept exists (Q4 asks about default-path safety), but the signal vocabulary doesn't capture the firmware-default-no-auth + LAN-trust-model shape.",
/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/board-review-data/scan-bundles/WLED-01328a6.json:5463:        "suggested_threshold_adjustment": "Add compute-side derivation: if the harness detects (tls_cors hit on `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *`) AND (auth_bypass hit count == 0 on a web-server-shipping tool) AND (install-path reaches end-user device with factory-default state), auto-set q4_has_critical_on_default_path=True. Would close this override for the firmware-default-no-auth class.",
/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/board-review-data/scan-bundles/browser_terminal-9a77c4a.json:1335:        "summary": "One scorecard override on Q4: Phase 3 advisory computed amber via the standard rubric (q4_has_critical_on_default_path=False, since the dangerous-primitives regex doesn't read README or install-doc text). Phase 4 reads installation.md directly and finds the F0 typosquat URL on the Chrome install path. override_reason = harness_coverage_gap (second scan in the catalog to use this label, after Kronos Q4). Fix surface is phase_1_harness.py: add install-doc URL parsing with TLD-deviation detection; when that lands, the signal would fire without needing Phase 4 override."
/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/board-review-data/scan-bundles/browser_terminal-9a77c4a.json:1910:        "rationale": "The Phase 3 advisory computed amber via compute.py's Q4 rubric (q4_all_channels_pinned=False, q4_artifact_verified=False, q4_has_critical_on_default_path=False \u2014 compute cannot see the README text where the critical actually lives). Phase 4 reads installation.md directly (E1) and finds `chrome.google.cm/webstore/detail/browser-terminal/nbnfihffeffdhcbblmekelobgmdccfnl` \u2014 a Cameroon-TLD typosquat in the Chrome install path. Cross-referenced against `chrome.google.com`, this is not a different domain under Google's control; it is a `.cm` lookalike that would silently serve whatever page its owner configures. Separately, the Go native-binary install step is `sudo mv ~/Downloads/browser_terminal_linux /usr/local/bin/browser_terminal` with no integrity verification (E3, E4) \u2014 no checksum file in the release, no sha256 step in the README. For a tool whose installed form is a native-messaging shell bridge, this combination is not amber-level; it's red. Firefox users following the (correct) addons.mozilla.org URL do not hit the typosquat, but they do still hit the unsigned-binary step \u2014 so the red call applies on the Chrome install path and amber on the Firefox-only path.",
/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/board-review-data/scan-bundles/browser_terminal-9a77c4a.json:1912:        "suggested_threshold_adjustment": "Add a harness step that fetches install-doc URLs (README hyperlinks matching /install/ or /web.?store/ or /addons/) and checks TLD against a reference list. Any Chrome install URL whose host is not `chrome.google.com` (or a redirect to it) should flag `q4_has_critical_on_default_path=true`. That single check would have fired on this repo without requiring Phase 4 override.",
/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/v12-wild-scan-telemetry.md:66:**What WLED (25) added (2nd break)**: a **confirmed, specific, remote-exploitable surface** (factory-default webserver has no auth + CORS wildcard + unauthenticated `/reset`) that's invisible to compute because the pattern lives in C++ control-flow (correctPIN gating logic tied to settingsPIN string length), not in a grep-able primitive family. `dangerous_primitives.tls_cors` DID surface the `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *` hit, but there's no compute derivation that combines `tls_cors_hit + no_auth_primitive_detected + firmware_shape → q4_has_critical_on_default_path=True`.
/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/v12-wild-scan-telemetry.md:78:**Signal added**: compute derives `q4_has_critical_on_default_path = True` when `dangerous_primitives.deserialization.hit_count >= N` AND the tool is documented as loading user files.
/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/v12-wild-scan-telemetry.md:92:**Signal-widening proposal**: compute derives `q4_has_critical_on_default_path = True` when `tls_cors.hit_count >= 1` (wildcard Origin/Methods/Headers pattern) AND `auth_bypass.hit_count == 0` (no auth-gate pattern detected) AND shape is `firmware | iot | on-device-webserver`. Shape classification would be a new compute-side input — bootstrappable from README keywords (ESP32, ESP8266, firmware, on-device, LAN webserver) + install-path signals (.bin releases, browser-WebSerial flasher).
/root/tinkering/stop-git-std/docs/v12-wild-scan-telemetry.md:100:**Signal-widening proposal**: compute derives `q4_has_critical_on_default_path = True` when README (Step 7.5 output) contains disclaimer phrases matching `(not affiliated|not endorsed|not authorized|reverse.?engineered|unofficial.*client)` AND topic list contains `reverse-engineering` OR the library name references a named platform (whatsapp, discord, instagram, telegram-client, facebook-messenger). This sits in the harness's Step 7.5 README paste-scan extension + Step 1a topic-field read; both already produce the raw data. The missing piece is the compound rule in compute that reads them.
